<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-08-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-08-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="434" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">United States Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-08-27"><hi rend="italic">August 27,
                                        1900</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p>(Mr. Choate is informed by foreign office that the British reply to
                                Li Hung Chang’s request to name envoy to negotiate is similar to
                                that <pb facs="0446" n="348" xml:id="pg_348"/> made by the United
                                States—that the views of Sir Claude McDonald must be had before Li
                                Hung Chang can be answered. The British Government cares little who
                                represents China if he is properly accredited; but is not satisfied
                                that Li Hung Chang is plenipotentiary or authorized by competent
                                authority to negotiate.)</p>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>